04094nam a22006375i 9780674029675DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20212008mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740296757 a10.4159/97806740296752doi  a(DE-B1597)574596  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHN373 -- C73 2008eb 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a303.6409409021 aCohn Jr., Samuel K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLust for Liberty :bThe Politics of Social Revolt in Medieval Europe, 1200-1425 /cSamuel K. Cohn Jr. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Introduction -- t2 Peasant Revolts -- t3 Economic Revolts -- t4 Varieties of Revolt -- t5 Leaders -- t6 Women, Ideology, and Repression -- t7 Communication and Alliances -- t8 Flags and Words -- t9 The Black Death and Change over Time -- t10 A New Appetite for Liberty -- tNotes -- tSources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLust for Liberty challenges long-standing views of popular medieval revolts. Comparing rebellions in northern and southern Europe over two centuries, Samuel Cohn analyzes their causes and forms, their leadership, the role of women, and the suppression or success of these revolts. Popular revolts were remarkably common--not the last resort of desperate people. Leaders were largely workers, artisans, and peasants. Over 90 percent of the uprisings pitted ordinary people against the state and were fought over political rights--regarding citizenship, governmental offices, the barriers of ancient hierarchies--rather than rents, food prices, or working conditions. After the Black Death, the connection of the word "liberty" with revolts increased fivefold, and its meaning became more closely tied with notions of equality instead of privilege. The book offers a new interpretation of the Black Death and the increase of and change in popular revolt from the mid-1350s to the early fifteenth century. Instead of structural explanations based on economic, demographic, and political models, this book turns to the actors themselves--peasants, artisans, and bourgeois--finding that the plagues wrought a new urgency for social and political change and a new self- and class-confidence in the efficacy of collective action.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674029675423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674029675.jpg  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)b2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK